{"id":14881581,"mediaExerciseId":"b382437f-c5ea-47cb-b7f0-bb042ceb9e2b","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"16","chapterTitle":"Financial Leverage and Capital Structure Policy","groupId":612420,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":573,"solutions":[{"id":6388181,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this question, we will determine which financing method maximizes the price per share of the firm. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The price per share of the firm is determined by its market value. As stated in the problem, the firm is all-equity which means that the value of the firm is based solely on their assets. \n\nAs stated in the previous problems, using a model that issues debt to finance some of its assets is a better way of maximizing the market value of the firm. It is better since it increases the firm's value and at the same time reduces the future taxes. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"From this, we know that the model that issues debt creates a higher market value, thus, a higher price per share for the firm's stock. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"1bafa572-249c-4e37-80b4-046235a2a3da","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corpora